ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, we report a detailed study of physicochemical properties and microstructure of EmimCl-EG DESs with the different EmimCl-EG molar ratios (from 2:1 to 1:2), which was used to be associated with their SO2 absorption behavior. To achieve the purpose of research, physicochemical properties, such as densities (ρ), viscosities (η), speeds of sound (u), refractive indices (nD
                     ), and thermal decomposition temperatures (T
                     d) of three DESs were measured, and other derived properties, such as thermal expansion coefficient (α
                     p) and activation energy for viscous flow (Eη
                     ), were calculated accordingly based on theory of thermodynamics. To get a better understanding of the effect of microstructure of EmimCl-EG DESs on their SO2 absorption behavior, NMR and IR spectroscopy, which have been successfully utilized to investigate the interaction of ILs and nanomaterials in the recent years [29–33], are employed to study the microstructure of EmimCl-EG DESs, especially to characterize the strength of the interactions in EmimCl and hydrogen bond interaction of OH⋯Cl− with the concentration of EG in DESs. Moreover, the influence of physicochemical properties and microstructure of EmimCl-EG DESs on SO2 absorption behavior was discussed, and the relationship between the SO2 absorption capacity and ρ or Eη
                      of EmimCl-EG DESs was explored.
